(defun extract-hidden-word (text)
  "Extracts the hidden word from a text string.
   Assumes the word is the last word after 'The secret word you are looking for is:'."
  (let ((start-string "The secret word you are looking for is:")
        (end-string "--- END OF TEXT ---"))
    (if (find start-string text)
        (let ((start-index (position start-string text))
              (end-index (position end-string text)))
          (if (> start-index end-index)
              (let ((substring (subseq text (+ start-index (length start-string)) end-index)))
                (string-trim '(#\Space #\Tab #\Newline) substring)))
            (error "Start string found after end string."))))))

;; Example Usage:
(let ((text (read-from-string
             "The secret word you are looking for is: SIGMA
--- END OF TEXT ---")))
(format t "Extracted word: ~A~%" (extract-hidden-word text))

from typing import List, Optional, Dict, Set, Any

class Solution:
    def extract_hidden_word(self, text: str) -> Optional[str]:
        """
        Extracts the hidden word from a text string.
        Assumes the word is the last word after 'The secret word you are looking for is:'
        and before '--- END OF TEXT ---'.

        Args:
            text: The input text string.

        Returns:
            The hidden word as a string, or None if the start or end string is not found
            or if the start string appears after the end string.
        """
        start_string = "The secret word you are looking for is:"
        end_string = "--- END OF TEXT ---"

        if start_string not in text or end_string not in text:
            return None

        start_index = text.find(start_string)
        end_index = text.find(end_string)

        if start_index > end_index:
            return None

        substring = text[start_index + len(start_string):end_index]
        return substring.strip()
